(b)

    They do not take the usual Terêna person‐prefixes or suffixes.

    my tin can = látana; my cloak = kápana

Problem 4
(a)
X = bi; missing in examples 4, 7, 10.

(b)
12. six betel nuts
13. one egg
14. six sugar canes
15. ten sheets of sago bark
16. thirteen sheets of sago bark

(c)
17. atut atub bøbys
18. anowip biagas atub juhurubys
19. atugu biabys juhurubys
20. atugu anowip biaruh atugas baigas

Problem 5
(a)
Generation 2 siblings:
Man 1 = Yaw; Woman 1 = Thema; Woman 2 = Ama.
Man 2 = Dubaku; Woman 3 = Kunto; Man 3 = Ofori.

Generation 3:
– Children of “Enu’s father”: Man 2 = Enu; Woman 2 = Nsia; Woman 3 = Awotwi.
– Children of Ofori: Man = Kofi; Woman = Esi.
– Child of Kunto: Man = Kobina (× Efua).

Generation 3 (cont’d):
– Children of Yaw (Man 1): Woman 4 = –; Man 4 = –.
– Child of Thema (Woman 1): Man 5 = – (× Woman 6 = –).

Generation 4:
– Children of Ama (Woman 2) × Enu (Man 2): Man 6 = –; Woman 6 = –.

(b)
Yaw: Yɛfrɛ me Yaw. Yɛfrɛ me ɛnanim Thema ne Ama. Yɛfrɛ me ɛnane Dubaku ne Ofori. Yɛfrɛ me nuanom Enu ne Nsia ne Awotwi. Yɛfrɛ me wɔfa Berko.

Kofi: Yɛfrɛ me Kofi. Yɛfrɛ me nua Esi. Yɛfrɛ me agya Ofori. Yɛfrɛ me sewaanom Yaw ne Ama. Yɛfrɛ me sewaabanom Thema ne Kobina.
